Notes:

Date: 0/0/1988
Source: Dictionary of Kiwi Slang, A
Author: McGILL
Vol / Page: 27
Edition:
Quote: <i>chop</i> share or cut; phr. <i>in for one's chop</i> selfishly interested in getting one's share and perhaps more; from the best cut of sheep or beef carcass; eg `Any hint of extra profits and Nat's in for his chop, no worries.' C. 1920, Australia c.1940. - <i>not much chop </i>of little value; from Anglo-Indian `first chop', first rate, from Hindi `chhap', a print, seal or brand; eg `All the fuss about this new supermarket. Prices are no different. I don't think it's much chop myself.' NZA.
